Objective: We the examine consequences of the summer 2022 heatwave for Italy.\

This project is loosely based on Ballester et al.Â (2023) who conduct a quantitative analysis of the mortality-temperature relationship using the NUTS3 spatial resolution (both for mortality figures and ERA5 temperature scans). Below, we use mortality data for the whole of Italy, so results will differ from those of Ballester et al.Â (2023).\

URL = None
KEY = None

# Traversing each line to extract the URL and key

    if line.startswith("url:"):
        URL = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
    elif line.startswith("key:"):
        KEY = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()

# Verification of extraction
if URL is None or KEY is None:
    raise ValueError("The URL or key was not found in the file.")

3 A simple time-series model of excess mortality 

#  Filter data up to March 1, 2020
mortality_ref <- mortality %>%
  filter(start_date < as.Date("2020-03-01"))

# Building a linear model
#    - factor(week) to have a fixed effect (a "dummification" of the week)
#    - year as numeric (for a linear trend) or factor(year) (for a fixed effect per year)
mod <- lm(mortality ~ factor(week) + year, data = mortality_ref)

# Check a model summary
summary(mod)

Predicting for the summer of 2022 and calculating excess mortality 

# Extract mortality for the summer of 2022 (dates to be adapted according to the desired period)
mortality_2022 <- mortality %>%
  filter(year == 2022, 
         start_date >= as.Date("2022-06-01"), 
         start_date <= as.Date("2022-08-31"))  # for example until the end of September

# Apply your linear model prediction
mortality_2022 <- mortality_2022 %>%
  mutate(predicted = predict(mod, newdata = mortality_2022),
         excess    = mortality - predicted)  # excess mortality

predicted : the mortality predicted by your model.

excess : the observed difference â predicted. A positive value indicates more deaths than the model would have predicted, and therefore potentially excess mortality.

Visualisation

ggplot(mortality_2022, aes(x = start_date, y = excess)) +

The graph shows the evolution of excess mortality (excess deaths compared to forecasts) in Italy during the summer of 2022, with two distinct peaks. The first peak in July reached about 2800 excess deaths, followed by a temporary decline, then a second much larger peak at the end of July/beginning of August culminating at about 4400 deaths. This excess mortality clearly coincides with the periods of high temperatures observed in the previous graphs, particularly with the intense heat wave at the end of July/beginning of August when temperatures exceeded 27Â°C.
